    <section id="fun-facts">
        <div class="container">
            <div class="row">
                <p>
                    I have experience working in technology as a Systems Administrator and I'm pivoting my
                    career path to Development. Software Development and Programming have always interested me and I think now is the
                    perfect time for me to change paths. I have experience with Windows, Linux, Computer Hardware, and various types of Enterprise Software Systems.
                    I like infrastructure and I'm really good and it but the field is overly crowded, offers less compensation, and is
                    more "competitive" than ever. I believe that  the traditional Systems Admin role that the industry has known for the
                    past decade is fading, but these roles are changing into a position for someone who has the traditional SysAdmin skills but who can
                    also code. I think biggest reason the traditional SysAdmin market is shrinking, is because of more affordable
                    cloud hosting. Cost effective cloud hosting is causing many companies to vitrualize the bulk of their infrastructure and, many
                    software companies are utlizing the cloud and changing their business models to subscription-based SaaS model. Both
                    of these things contribute to less need for System Admins and more need for specific Admins that are application/system centric.
                    From personal experience, most companies that are looking to fill traditional Systems Admins
                    positions are requiring 10+ years of experience and care less about what skills a candidate has. Software
                    development on the other hand is about experience, but more about what you know and what your skills are. This is important
                    to me because I am a quick learner and I enjoy learning about all aspects of technology.
                </p>
